That's how I currently understand what you are trying to do (but I'm really unsure if I understand that correctly):

* You have a scenario where the "host" loads other containers as "plugins"
* Plugins want to access shared libraries from the host, e. g. react
* Plugins want to access exposed modules from the host, e. g. app name

Not sure if this is correct, because it's very different from the linked issues.

If this is correct, my question is "why doesn't that work with the current implementation in your case?"

``` js
// in the host
new ModuleFederationPlugin({
  name: "host", // this also defines the name of the global
  filename: "container.js",
  exposes: {
    "./AppName": "./src/app-name.js"
  },
  shared: {
    react: { singleton: true }
  }
})

// in the plugin
new ModuleFederationPlugin({
  name: "myPlugin",
  shared: {
    react: { singleton: true }
  },
  remotes: {
    // host remote is available in a global variable
    host: "var host"
  }
})
```

in the host HTML make sure to load `container.js` before the `app.js` to make sure it's available for plugins. (or at least before loading plugins)

@sokra i will answer in multiple parts

one of the main problems with MF is that only works in async mode and if u want to build a component that can be imported in NPM as a package this fails in weird modes because we have to do the bootstrap setup to avoid do the initial load in webpack, and also contain multiple problems like the next

* as a plugin if i want to consume exposed modules from host i have to load it as "remote" but that doesnt make sense because the host is who is LOADING the plugin, and in that moment those modules should be already loaded, to avoid do breaking changes i introduced a new kind of "remote" called `host` like the next example

 ```
new ModuleFederationPlugin({
        name: `PlitziPlugin${PluginName.charAt(0).toUpperCase() + PluginName.slice(1)}Federation`,
        filename: `plitzi-plugin-${PluginName}-federation.js`,
        remotes: {
          plitziSdkFederation: [
            'plitziSdkFederation@host'
          ]
        },
        exposes: {
          Plugin: './src/component/index.js'
        },
        shared: {
          react: { singleton: true, requiredVersion: PACKAGE.dependencies.react },
          'react-dom': { singleton: true, requiredVersion: PACKAGE.dependencies['react-dom'] },
          'react-redux': { singleton: true, requiredVersion: PACKAGE.dependencies['react-redux'] }
        }
      })
```
if we can see here, i am telling to webpack that the remote `plitziSdkFederation` is my host and i want to be consumed this as sync way because his exposed modules should be already loaded and this will prevent to load twice the remote because doesnt make any sense

* second point, shared modules should be loaded in order to be sure that they will be available when plugin modules will be loaded and the way to acomplish this was keeping them as eager mode

* third point, exposed modules now will be considered shared also, because they will be available always from the host, and for this i introduced a new OPTIONAL way to handle this

```
new ModuleFederationPlugin({
        name: 'plitziSdkFederation',
        filename: 'plitzi-sdk-federation.js',
        exposes: {
          './usePlitziServiceContext': { import: './src/services/hooks/usePlitziServiceContext', shared: true },
          './ComponentContext': { import: './src/modules/Component/ComponentContext', shared: true },
          './ComponentProvider': { import: './src/modules/Component/ComponentProvider', shared: true }
        },
        shared: [
          {
            react: { singleton: true, requiredVersion: false, eager: true },
            'react-dom': { singleton: true, requiredVersion: false, eager: true },
            'react-redux': { singleton: true, requiredVersion: false, eager: true }
          }
        ]
      })
```
as we can see i added a new optional attribute called `shared` in exposed modules, so this is telling to webpack that these modules must be available as shared before load any plugin to be sure that they will be available and wont be separated in chunks

also i introduced an important change in sharedPlugin where i can be able to share modules across nested bundles compiled to fix the problem with react for example that was crashing with the error `react is duplicated` the common error with hooks

https://github.com/webpack/webpack/pull/15271/files#diff-c3b1610b00ec187ec39f60ef90682220aef7392d2943458cc005d123cbcd8dd9R80 (when nested webpack bundles are compiled for second time, i was able to handle these scenarios to support sharePlugin in a better way)

all of these changes are optional to grant the functionality in sync scenarios.

the main reasons of this change are:
*  MF only works in async mode (host and plugins)
* you cant import a plugin inside another plugin using NPM (the normal way) because the index.js is async loading a bootstrap https://webpack.js.org/concepts/module-federation/#troubleshooting (this weird way to setup MF using bootstrap.js)
* if i want to have multiple hosts that imports their plugins is not possible because always is loading the host as remote
* i want to be able to load plugins as remote plugins in a controlled way like was suggested in the docs but also i want to have the way to import those plugins as NPM package way 

```
 import Plugin from 'pluginA';
<Host>
  <Plugin />
</Host>
```

* when plugins are compiled with MF plugin they cant be used like the previous way or forcing me use lazy loads everytime making harder to manage it because the default export is a promise


from your example, how can you handle the scenario where you have multiple hosts loading the same plugin, and i am asking this because i am building a web/widgets builder, with the current solution there are many limitations and unnecesary complexity to consume MF

